Well, walk without pain in my hips, my knee and ankle aren’t going to improve.

Related, I need to do exercises every day to be able to walk without pain, but the exercises are boring and painful and have no immediate effect so my ADHD brain won’t allow them to be 2 minutes in the morning.
TL;DR you can do everything right and you still won’t always get the outcome you want. Acceptance is the key. Acceptance isn’t pessimism.

Most abled people have never had to experience this and so see acceptance as pessimism, defeat, and self pity. So in talking to them you have to explain that knowing yourself isn’t talking yourself down, it’s just having realistic expectations of your abilities

Living with chronic health conditions requires accepting that the job of medicine is just to make your body fail more slowly, as that allows you to move on and live your life fully rather than clinging to false hope.

One of the tiring things about talking with abled people about your conditions is that they view the world in a way that not only can everything be fixed, it will be fixed if you just do everything right, and negative experiences are one-offs rather than just how things are.

Often when a new communication technology, such as the printing press and the telegraph arrives it becomes a free for all nightmare that has huge social costs as well as benefits,
